The user updates his self-description as follows: I now prefer intimate, harmony‑first mixes: close‑mic’d, mono/tape warmth with crystalline, multitracked harmonies and a tactile, forward lead vocal; melody‑first sequencing and low‑compression remasters that preserve micro‑dynamics and headroom. I like restrained low end that supports vocals rather than dominates, minimal reverb for immediate presence, and polished vocal balances that keep lyrics and harmonies clear and cohesive. From earlier tastes I retain a love of tasteful analogue coloration (subtle tape/tube saturation), clear separation and harmony‑aware arrangements, tactile grand piano and concise, hook‑forward sequencing. I dislike mixes that prioritize heavy, punchy low end and pumped, radio‑style limiting; brittle, glassy processing; over‑layered rooms that swamp vocal detail; and productions that chase transient micro‑detail or guitar minutiae at the expense of melodic and harmonic cohesion.

The positive CD has the following updated information: Sounds of Summer: Very Best of The Beach Boys — mono/tape warmth with crystalline, multitracked harmonies; surprisingly tactile drums and focused, supportive low end; minimal reverb and low‑compression remaster preserve micro‑dynamics while polished midrange and sequencing add melodic hooks and rhythmic drive. Ideal for listeners wanting harmony plus momentum.

